    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8c3e26e868ee32c1",
      "text": "Usually, basic IP clients attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "42405eba37dee6c6ea565f93bc26de4d",
      "text": "There is no standard procedure for deciding which address will be used by the requesting application, a few resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically \"closer\" networks. Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of 30–45 seconds."
    },
